00:09:39.130 --> 00:09:44.040
My topic for today is
Marriage and Politics in 19th

00:09:44.040 --> 00:09:47.150
and 20th Century Ethiopia.

00:09:47.150 --> 00:09:52.300
Before I begin, I should say
as mirrors and cars usually say

00:09:52.300 --> 00:09:57.630 position:56%
"Objects in the mirror appear closer
than actually their distance".

00:09:57.630 --> 00:10:00.850
This material is extremely
dense material.

00:10:00.850 --> 00:10:04.040
And at one point or another your
eyes are going to glaze over

00:10:04.040 --> 00:10:07.850
and your mind is going to go blank
and I won't take it personally

00:10:07.850 --> 00:10:11.940
because this was my life for 10
years, and it's pretty dense stuff.

00:10:11.940 --> 00:10:15.880
But I'll try - what I'll try to
do is go into some details for -

00:10:15.880 --> 00:10:19.930
to show or illustrate examples
and kind of move back out to kind

00:10:19.930 --> 00:10:22.920
of talk about the larger
significance of things.

00:10:27.120 --> 00:10:30.820
The universality of the topic
of marriage as a political

00:10:30.820 --> 00:10:34.940
and diplomatic instrument, a
symbolic show of solidarity

00:10:34.940 --> 00:10:38.140
and socially accepted way to
cement relations across kingdoms

00:10:38.140 --> 00:10:42.660
and countries is one that we can
attest to here, anywhere really

00:10:42.660 --> 00:10:48.170
around the world at any
time of any time period.

00:10:48.170 --> 00:10:52.160
You may remember those of you who
have followed Pan African history

00:10:52.160 --> 00:10:57.120
for example, the marriage
of Ghana's Kwame Nkrumah

00:10:57.120 --> 00:11:01.200 position:56%
to a woman named Helena Ritz Fathia.

00:11:01.200 --> 00:11:02.880
The woman was a close relative

00:11:02.880 --> 00:11:05.680
of President Gamal
Abdel Nasser of Egypt.

00:11:05.680 --> 00:11:08.020
And they got married in 1958.

00:11:08.020 --> 00:11:12.000
And the time Ghanian kente cloth
weavers commemorated the occasion

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:15.670
by designing patterns such
as Fathia, Fata and Nkrumaha,

00:11:15.670 --> 00:11:19.090
which means it is befitting to
have Fathia as in Nkrumah's wife

00:11:19.090 --> 00:11:23.920
and Oba Kofu Muman, one
person does not rule a nation.

00:11:23.920 --> 00:11:25.600
They had three children
together and up

00:11:25.600 --> 00:11:28.960
until recently they
maintained residents in Ghana.

00:11:28.960 --> 00:11:33.990
We may also think about Jomo
Kenyatta's marriages, the third

00:11:33.990 --> 00:11:37.730
and fourth marriages were to
daughters of influential chiefs,

00:11:37.730 --> 00:11:42.920
which helped him gain legitimacy
for leadership among the Kikuyu.

00:11:42.920 --> 00:11:45.470
In Europe of course,
European history is replete

00:11:45.470 --> 00:11:48.830
with these examples between
11th and 20th century.

00:11:48.830 --> 00:11:54.110
European royalty from France,
Britain, Spain, Prussia, Denmark,

00:11:54.110 --> 00:11:58.230
Russia and Germany inter-married
very, very extensively

00:11:58.230 --> 00:12:02.470
and there are also examples in the
colonial setting here for example

00:12:02.470 --> 00:12:06.850
that Spanish conquistadors
married Amerindian women

00:12:06.850 --> 00:12:10.660
in the 16th Century, French
commercial entrepreneurs in Senegal

00:12:10.660 --> 00:12:14.710
for example made a point of
marrying powerful trade women,

00:12:14.710 --> 00:12:19.460
known as sinaras to gain acceptance
and access to commercial networks.

00:12:19.460 --> 00:12:24.010
In the Ethiopian case my study
is limited to the Northern part

00:12:24.010 --> 00:12:28.470
of the country because my sense of
it was I wanted to study marriage,

00:12:28.470 --> 00:12:32.520
but in connection to politics, not
just marriage as it was happening.

00:12:32.520 --> 00:12:37.110
But in connection to political
history and but it's fair to say

00:12:37.110 --> 00:12:40.900
that a similar study could be
designed for south and west

00:12:40.900 --> 00:12:45.320
of the country, in the area
of Wolayta, Naria and Keffiyeh

00:12:45.320 --> 00:12:48.870 position:56%
where migration and marriage
relations are very important element

00:12:48.870 --> 00:12:52.430
and consolidation from the
17 through the 19th century.

00:12:52.430 --> 00:12:57.600
By way of background
and introduction a lot

00:12:57.600 --> 00:13:02.110
of my presentation today
draws from research I did

00:13:02.110 --> 00:13:04.110
for my dissertation study.

00:13:04.110 --> 00:13:08.570
The dissertation was titled
"Building Bridges Drying Bad Blood.

00:13:08.570 --> 00:13:11.930
Elite Marriages, Politics
and Ethnicity in 19th

00:13:11.930 --> 00:13:13.590
and 20th Century Ethiopia".

00:13:13.590 --> 00:13:18.760
So, it came about because at a
very visceral level I grew up,

00:13:18.760 --> 00:13:21.750
as most Ethiopians,
grew up understanding

00:13:21.750 --> 00:13:25.780
that Ethiopia was an interconnected
space, we were intermarried,

00:13:25.780 --> 00:13:28.210
was all one big happy family.

00:13:28.210 --> 00:13:32.290
And as I got older and read
more and listened more,

00:13:32.290 --> 00:13:36.020
I grew anxious I think at
some subconscious level

00:13:36.020 --> 00:13:39.400
about the polarized way in
which discussions were happening

00:13:39.400 --> 00:13:43.890
around state building and identity,
both in conventional scholarship

00:13:43.890 --> 00:13:48.250
and in public discourse and of
course lately in social media.

00:13:48.250 --> 00:13:52.260
My advisor was Harold
Markus at Michigan State.

00:13:52.260 --> 00:13:54.360
And he was very worried
that I was going

00:13:54.360 --> 00:13:59.070
to write what he called
a begot dissertation

00:13:59.070 --> 00:14:01.310
in the style of the Old Testament.

00:14:01.310 --> 00:14:04.170
So and so, so and so
begot so and so.

00:14:04.170 --> 00:14:06.680
And tempting as though that was,

00:14:06.680 --> 00:14:09.280
which means I could have had
an Old Testament under my belt.

00:14:09.280 --> 00:14:13.760
But as it was the research
took shape and it crystalized

00:14:13.760 --> 00:14:16.440
around three interwoven
threads or themes.

00:14:16.440 --> 00:14:20.650
Ethnicity, identity on the one
hand, movement of political power

00:14:20.650 --> 00:14:24.530
and state building and
then gender and women.

00:14:24.530 --> 00:14:28.590
I drew the theoretical frame
and methodology from readings

00:14:28.590 --> 00:14:32.600 position:56%
on ethnicity, theoretical
readings, gender and state building.

00:14:32.600 --> 00:14:35.470
I relied a lot on the
work of Anthropologists,

00:14:35.470 --> 00:14:40.510
the anthropologist couple John and
Jean Comaroff who defined ethnicity

00:14:40.510 --> 00:14:44.020
as a set of contextual relations
and therefore a more kind of fluid

00:14:44.020 --> 00:14:47.000 position:56%
and complex product of human agency.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:49.410
To examine gender and
the place of women,

00:14:49.410 --> 00:14:52.110
and this was extremely
difficult in the case of Ethiopia

00:14:52.110 --> 00:14:55.540
because they don't show up
in written records much.

00:14:55.540 --> 00:14:59.140
So I had to read widely to
come to the questions even.

00:14:59.140 --> 00:15:01.060
And I considered writings
by scholars

00:15:01.060 --> 00:15:04.310
who had explored the subject of
state building through kinship

00:15:04.310 --> 00:15:07.830
or marriage relations in places
like the Kingdom of Dowmy

00:15:07.830 --> 00:15:09.740
in Western West Central Africa.

00:15:09.740 --> 00:15:13.500
And the 19th century
Zulu and Boganda states.

00:15:13.500 --> 00:15:16.680
And from these readings I
eventually designed an inquiry

00:15:16.680 --> 00:15:20.260 position:56%
that would combine
methodological and thematic concerns

00:15:20.260 --> 00:15:22.420
and examine issues
of power, identity,

00:15:22.420 --> 00:15:24.510
gender and state formation.

00:15:24.510 --> 00:15:27.850
By documenting and studying
Ethiopian elite inter-marriages

00:15:27.850 --> 00:15:29.910
and family histories I set

00:15:29.910 --> 00:15:34.000
out to map what I call a
social history of power.

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:37.560
This meant focusing on elite family
histories and inter-relations

00:15:37.560 --> 00:15:41.050
and also reading this against the
narrative of political history.

00:15:41.050 --> 00:15:44.360
So it wasn't just genealogical
trees and family histories,

00:15:44.360 --> 00:15:48.740
but how that related to shifts of
power that I was interested in.

00:15:48.740 --> 00:15:51.760
My study evolves against
the backdrop of 19th

00:15:51.760 --> 00:15:53.690
and 20th century Ethiopia, a period

00:15:53.690 --> 00:15:56.900
of intense intermittent
power struggles, unification,

00:15:56.900 --> 00:16:00.540
territorial expansion
and later consolidation.

00:16:00.540 --> 00:16:01.950
Not surprisingly the pattern

00:16:01.950 --> 00:16:05.740 position:56%
of elite inter-marriage followed the
movement of power from [Inaudible],

00:16:05.740 --> 00:16:08.550
laterally including [Inaudible].

00:16:08.550 --> 00:16:14.970
The marriages usually occurred as
part of other power negotiations.

00:16:14.970 --> 00:16:20.270
As a prelude of good will and
attempt to address past wrongs,

00:16:20.270 --> 00:16:23.400
[Inaudible] is what it's called,
marriages to dry bad blood

00:16:23.400 --> 00:16:26.800
between families, or as marking
measure of close relations

00:16:26.800 --> 00:16:28.970
between regional nobility.

00:16:28.970 --> 00:16:30.340
Tenuous and fragile

00:16:30.340 --> 00:16:34.230
as they sometimes were these
alliances provided a critical

00:16:34.230 --> 00:16:37.290
continuum across geographical,
cultural,

00:16:37.290 --> 00:16:40.150
linguistic and political divides.

00:16:40.150 --> 00:16:43.270
Studying Ethiopian elite
inter-marriage also presented a

00:16:43.270 --> 00:16:46.330
novel opportunity to
explore the place of women.

00:16:46.330 --> 00:16:51.010
Although they're not visible in
public records as wives, daughters

00:16:51.010 --> 00:16:54.560
and mothers of royalty, Ethiopian
women were social, cultural

00:16:54.560 --> 00:16:57.330
and political actors
of some influence.

00:16:57.330 --> 00:17:01.300
By re-examining new and old
sources in this light I intended

00:17:01.300 --> 00:17:04.410
to find a place or configure
a place of prominence

00:17:04.410 --> 00:17:05.990
for the lives of elite women.

00:17:05.990 --> 00:17:09.260
And in the process takes steps
towards engendering Ethiopian

00:17:09.260 --> 00:17:11.700
political and social history.

00:17:11.700 --> 00:17:14.570
Now there are previous works
that have been published

00:17:14.570 --> 00:17:17.320
and that are fairly
good, they're out there.

